:"1244–Deceased","29 Jul 1941":"29 July 1941","1244":"1244","29 Jun 1939":"29 June 1939","1265":"1265","1264":"1264","1242":"1242","1274":"1274","about 1265":"about 1265","1292":"1292","Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Aylesbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Aylesbury (Bucks) or possibly Aylesbeare (Devon)."],"variants":[{"name":"Alesbury","meanings":["English:  see  Aylesbury  ."]},{"name":"Elsbury","meanings":["English: habitational name from Aylesbury (Buckinghamshire), from an Old English personal name <i>Ægel</i> (genitive <i>Ægeles</i>, <i>Ægles</i>) + <i>burg</i> ‘fortified place’ (dative <i>byrig</i>)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Aylesbury was born in 1244, in Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She married William Aylesbury in 1264, in Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1244–":"1244–Surnud","1242–1274":"1242–12